    "education": {
      "type": "advertorial-education",
      "settings": {
        "subhead": "What no one told you about menopause.",
        "body": "<p>Here's what's actually happening.</p><p>During perimenopause and menopause, your hormone levels shift — and your body's ability to absorb and use certain nutrients drops with them. Nutritional research on women over 40 has documented this pattern clearly. Calcium. Magnesium. Iron. Vitamin D. Anti-inflammatory compounds your joints used to get enough of without you thinking about it. All of them decline.</p><p>That morning stiffness? It's not wear and tear. It's your joints running on empty.</p><p>The exhaustion that doesn't match your effort? Your cells aren't getting the fuel they used to. The hot flashes, the sleep that never goes deep enough, the skin that suddenly feels thinner and drier — these aren't separate problems. They are all the same problem showing up in different places.</p><p>Clinical nutritionists who work with women in this age group have a term for it: systemic nutrient depletion. The body isn't failing. It's simply running out of raw materials it used to recycle efficiently — and once hormone levels shift, the deficit accelerates.</p><p><strong>Your body isn't breaking down. It's running out of what it needs.</strong> And here's the part that matters: this is not inevitable. It is a gap. And gaps can be filled.</p>"
      }
    },
    "why-nothing-works": {
      "type": "advertorial-why-nothing-works",
      "settings": {
        "subhead": "Why pushing through isn't working anymore.",
        "body_before_image": "<p>Most women in this phase respond the same way: they treat each symptom separately. A cream for the joints. Coffee for the energy. A sleep aid for the insomnia. Maybe a bottle of calcium or a turmeric capsule someone recommended. None of these are wrong. But none of them are working — and there's a simple reason why.</p>",
        "analogy_image": "shopify://shop_images/most-women-in-this-phase-respond-the-same-way-they-treat-each-symptom-separately-a-cream-for-the-joints-coffee-for-the-energy-a-sleep-aid-for-the-insomnia-maybe-a-bottle-of-calcium-or.png",
        "body_after_image": "<p>Imagine your house loses its main power supply. Every room goes dark. You could light a candle in each room — and that helps, temporarily. But what you actually need is to restore the source.</p><p>The body works the same way. When the underlying nutrient foundation drops, symptoms show up everywhere at once. Addressing them one by one is lighting candles. What the body needs is the power turned back on.</p><p>That's what leads many women to moringa — a plant known for delivering broad-spectrum nutrition in a single source. But not all moringa delivers on that promise. Some women try it and feel nothing. The brown powder for Rp 50,000 that tastes bitter and sits heavy — a week later, nothing has changed. What most don't realize is that what they tried was mostly ground-up stems their body couldn't absorb.</p><p>By the time most women reach this point — after the creams, the supplements, the powders that didn't work — the frustration has been building for years.</p>",
        "quote_text": "\"Saya 49 tahun. Sendi kaku, hot flash, emosi kacau, kulit kering. Udah agak desperate.\"",
        "quote_attribution": "Via Instagram DM"
      }
    },
    "moringa-education": {
      "type": "advertorial-moringa-education",
      "settings": {
        "subhead": "Restoring the source — not just lighting candles.",
        "body_before_callout": "<p>Recent nutritional research on women's health over 40 points to a different approach: instead of targeting symptoms one at a time, address the underlying depletion with a broad, dense spectrum of bioavailable nutrients — delivered consistently, in a form the body can actually use.</p><p>One plant matches this profile unusually well. Moringa oleifera contains over 90 bioavailable nutrients in a single leaf — including anti-inflammatory compounds, calcium, magnesium, iron, and zinc. Not as isolated chemicals in a lab, but as a complete nutritional profile the body recognizes and absorbs naturally.</p><p>For women in perimenopause and menopause, this matters. The gap isn't one nutrient. It's dozens. Moringa delivers them together, the way food does — not the way a supplement label does.</p>",
        "fact_label": "From published nutritional analyses",
        "fact_text": "<p>Moringa leaf contains 7× the vitamin C of oranges, 4× the calcium of milk, 3× the potassium of bananas, and 25× the iron of spinach — in a single, bioavailable source. Studies published in the Journal of Food Science and Technology and the Asian Pacific Journal of Tropical Biomedicine have documented its anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, and hormone-balancing properties.</p>",
        "comparison_image": "shopify://shop_images/moringa-leaf-contains-7-the-vitamin-c-of-oranges-4-the-calcium-of-milk-3-the-potassium-of-bananas-and-25-the-iron-of-spinach-in-a-single-bioavailable-source-studies-published-in-the-j.png",
        "body_after_callout": "<p>That covers what's happening inside the body. But remember the skin that suddenly feels thinner and drier? The hair that's lost its density? That's the same depletion — showing up on the surface. Moringa seed oil addresses this from the outside. It contains 72% oleic acid — a fatty acid that closely resembles the skin's own sebum — along with behenic acid and concentrated antioxidants. During menopause, when the skin loses moisture faster than it can rebuild, this oil feeds it directly what it's missing.</p><p>Nourishment from the inside. Nourishment from the outside. The question isn't whether moringa works. It's whether the moringa you try is good enough to make a difference.</p>"
      }
    },
